      <tr><td colspan=1  style='font-size: 9.5px;'>606 threads, <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=0>1</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=25>2</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=50>3</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=75>4</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=100>5</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=125>6</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=150>7</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=175>8</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=200>9</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=225>10</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=250>11</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=275>12</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=300>13</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=325>14</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=350>15</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=375>16</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=400>17</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=425>18</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=450>19</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=475>20</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=500>21</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=525>22</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=550>23</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=575>24</a> <a href=classes.html?class=4&start=600>25</a>  page(s) long</td><td  style='font-size: 9.5px;' align=right>&nbsp;<a href=classes.html?class=4&start=25>Next Page</a></td></tr></table></form><a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=4>Root thread</a><table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96661533329207></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96661533329207><tr><td id=headerrow><span id=sj>Four Songs/Multiple Instruments</span></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 12:15 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Hail!<br><br>This is written with the assumption that you can twist three songs pretty much all the time with ease.&nbsp;&nbsp;It also assumes that you have songs hotkeyed.  You also must have at least your offhand melee slot hotkeyed.  The reason to have everything hotkeyed is because lag will slow down your mouse movements if you try and hit the spell gems, which will make twisting four songs impossible.  You also need the mouse to move around instruments (more later).<br><br>The underlying trick to twisting four songs is that whenever you play a song, there is a point during the initial singing of it where you can quit before the song "goes off" and move onto the next song, but the effect still occurs.  This is about 3 seconds into each song (more on this later).  Try it out yourself with a song, stop it about three seconds in and then see it go off a few moments later even though you stopped singing.<br><br>Now to twists four songs you need to have a sense of internal rhythm, because what you need to do when you start the first song is start counting, either the numbers or, like I do it, slowly rocking in my chair (call me a freak :) ).  After three beats go by, using the hotkeys, relatively quickly hit the next song's hotkey twice.  This takes its own pacing, since you can hit it too fast and the next spell won't start.  Three beats, next song.  Three beats, next song.  You just did it, twisted four songs!<br><br>Now, let me say that you probably didn't actually succeed the first time.  Don't worry, it takes quite a bit of practice to get the timing down, but after a few hell levels of twisting four songs every battle, you'll get it. :)<br><br>NOTE:  Lag is your bane.  Anything that causes lag will prevent you from twisting four songs, slow internet connection, slow computer, huge dungeon with tons of battles going on or tons of other spell effects.  Have one song selected that you can drop from the rotation in a situation like this, and just twist three til the situation resolves.  Also try dropping resolution if it's related to particle effects of tons of creatures around.<br><br>Next is the multiple instruments during a fight.  Let's give an example, my lvl 48 bard in a group fight.  He's twisting four songs, Selo's Chords of Cessation (lvl 48 String-based DoT), Niv's Melody of Preservation (lvl 47 Strings-based party buff), Jonthan's Provocation (lvl 45 Brass-based party member buff) and Hymn of Restoration (lvl 6 Strings-based party heal).  Not saying I recommend this (only if you want your bard butchered), but say he's doing it.<br><br>Note that three of the songs are Strings-based and one is Brass-based.  You need to play the similar instrument ones together (you don't have to, but to keep your sanity do it).  In the above example, let's twist Jonthan's, Niv's, Hymn, and then the Chords as the Brass one.  Now using the hotkeyed offhand weapons slot slap the String instrument in.  Start singing using the song hotkeys.  A good layout to do this is to have the four songs in either slot 1-4 or 3-6 and cycle through them and then have the item slots in the other two.<br><br>While you are twisting through the first three songs, pick up the brass instrument.  After the song effect for Hymn kicks in (meaning you've already started playing Chords), swap the string instrument out and put the brass one in.  When the spell effect goes off you will get the brass effect.  Then, after the spell effect goes off (and you are singing Jonthan's again), swap out brass and put in the strings one again.  In essence: Jonthan's, Niv's, Hymn, Chords, Hymn effect, swap to brass, Jonthan's, Chords effect, swap to strings, Niv's, etc...<br><br>The trick here is realizing that the songs don't check for whether or not you have the correct instrument in the slot until the spell effect goes off.  This means that you need to keep the instrument for a song in until it goes off, even though you might be singing a different song, and then swap them before the new song goes off.<br><br>A few points before I finish.  Doing this will give you severe hand pain.  Only do this during battle, and then pick one song to play during the offtimes (usually mana song or hymn).  If your group doesn't understand, leave them.  When they see how pathetic they just became without you, they will.<br><br>Have your interface warn you from dropping instruments accidentally.  In the old days, if you were swapping instruments, it wasn't uncommon to drop one on the ground cuz of the lag in an environment.  Few things are "funnier" than watching a bard scrambling around trying to pick up the lute mid-battle.<br><br>All songs have some slight variation in the "3 seconds" that you need to sing them, either shorter or longer.  The longer ones will make it so that you can't twist four effectively, but coupled with shorter ones this will even out.  Once you get practice, you can twist them the same with little hiccups in your rhythm.  Some will also lose their effects sooner than others.  There really isn't a way around this, except you need to get better.  :)<br><br>I think this is all for now.  Hopefully I didn't forget anything...<br><br>Muse...<br>Bard and Cartographer<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
